Ventilation and perfusion of the lung

[!INFO] Ventilation and perfusion are BOTH greater at the bases
However, increase in blood (from top to bottom) is greater than the increase in ventilation (from top to bottom).
Therefore, overall, V/Q ratio decreases from top to bottom.

$$
\frac{V}{Q}{top} > \frac{\large{↑V}}{\Large{↑↑Q}}{bottom}
$$

In a healthy individual, the V/Q ratio is 1 at the middle of the lung, with a minimal spread of V/Q ratios from 0.3 to 2.1 from base to apex. Source

Ventilation:
Less negative intrapleural pressure at the base -> lower transmural difference at the base -> Basal alveoli are less expanded -> Therefore, they are more compliant -> Therefore, large change in volume during inspiration -> bases have higher ventilation.

Perfusion:
Perfusion is also greater at the bases.

[!INFO] These are usually attributed to gravity
because these variations decrease in the supine position.
However, they are still present in weightlessness of space.

Possible effect of V/Q ratio on alveolar PO2

In cases of high V/Q ratios, PO2 increases and PCO2 decreases as alveolar air more closely matches the larger volume of inspired air than perfused blood. On the other hand, low V/Q ratios result in a decreased PO2 and an increased PCO2. Source
So ? alveolar PO2 would be higher at the top and lower at the bottom of the lung.

Pulmonary vascular resistance

Pulmonary mean arterial pressure = 15mmHg.
Mean pulmonary venous pressure (= LAP = wedge pressure) = 5mmHg.

[!INFO] How to rember:
PA = alveolar;
Pa - arterial, Pv - venous
The position of PA progressively moves to the right side of the comparison; it becomes lower and lower relative to the vascular pressures.

The lower the alveolar pressures, the less distended they are -> less pressure on the vessels -> less vascular resistance.
Vascular resistance is lowest in zone 3 and HIGHEST IN ZONE 1 Source

Effect of anatomic dead space

Rapid breathing at low tidal volume and slow breathing at large tidal volume both result in the same minute ventilation.
But because of anatomical dead space, with rapid shallow breathing, less air reaches the alveoli resulting in significantly less alveolar ventilation.


Most dietary iron is in the Ferric Fe3+ form but absorption requires the Fe2+ forms. Therefore, brush border has ferric reductase enzyme. Gastric acid is required for iron to for complexes with ascorbic acid so that it can be reduced.
Partial gastrectomy therefore causes iron deficiency.

Iron elimination is a zero order process. Which is probably why [[2021 General Medicine July#Iron FESO4 / sulphate overdose]] causes toxicity.

Cholinergic crisis

Cholinergic hyperstimulation secondary to inhibition of acetylcholinesterase enzyme.
Symptoms: hypersalivation, lacrimation, muscle weakness, paralysis, blurry vision due to both nitocinic and muscarinic toxicity.

Efficacy and potency

#2018BSQ-OCT/Q02
Efficacy is the maximum effect that a drug can exert.
Potency is the concentration/dose of drug required to exert 50% of it's maximal effect.
Source

Efficacy:


A has higher efficacy than B.
But the dose at which 50% of maximum drug effect is achieved for Both A and B are similar. (?so similar potency?)

Therapeutic efficacy and pharmacological efficacy

The concept above is therapeutic efficacy.
Pharmacological efficay (also called Intrinsic efficacy) is

is the drug's maximal efficacy as a fraction of the maximal efficacy produced by a full agonist of the same type acting through the same receptors under the same conditions

Potency


A and B have the same maximum effect (i.e same efficacy) but A achieves this at a lower dose; Therefore, A is more potent.

![efficacy and potency.jpg](efficacy and potency.jpg)

Drug B is more potent than Drug A. Drug A and B have the same efficacy.
However, A has a steeper dose response curve so it requires a smaller increase in dose than B to achieve maximum effect.

#2018BSQ-OCT/Q15

[!INFO] TIP: NALF is not NALFD
NALF is the mild end of NAFLD; NALFD is a collective term

Histologically looks like alcoholic liver disease but patient does not have a Hx of significant alcohol consumption.

[!WARNING] NASH progresses to cirrhosis in 20% of patients!

  • Central obesity
  • type 2 diabetes mellitus
  • dyslipidemia,
    NALFD is considered to be the hepatic component of metabolic syndrome.

📑Pathophysiology of NAFLD

📑Insulin resistance is the key prerequisite for NAFLD.

Insulin resistance leads to increased lipolysis, triglyceride synthesis, increased hepatic uptake of free fatty acids (FFA), and accumulation of hepatic triglyceride

Oxidative stress may then lead to lipid peroxidation.

Histology of NAFL (and alcoholic liver disease)

3 main changes occurring in various degrees and combinations:

  • Steatosis (fatty change), Hepatitis (inflammation) and Fibrosis

Steatosis:
Starts with fat accumulation in centrilobular areas and then spreads outwards. The liver will be soft, yellow and greasy. (i.e starts in ZONE 3)

Steatohepatitis
This stage is more common in alcoholic hepatitis than NAFL.
Shows

  • Hepatocyte ballooning with necrosis
  • Intracellular eosinophilic includions: Mallody Denk bodies
  • Neutrophil infiltration to remove the necrotic hepatocytes and those with Mallory Denk bodies.

Fibirosis

  • Also appears in zone 3 and spread outwards. (central vein sclerosis)
  • Perisinusoidal scarring in space of disse also similary spreads outwards
  • Fibrosis spreads in chicken wire fence pattern
  • The fibrosis reach the protal tracts and creates central-portal fibrous septa.
  • These changes cause micronodular cirrhosis. (aka Laennec cirrhosis)
  • Chronically, the liver becomes shrunken but with cirrhotic nodules which are smaller than in other causes like viral hepatitis.

Investigations

  • Mild increases in ALT and AST with ALT > AST; mild elevation of gamma-GT.
  • USS Shows steatosis
  • Biopsy : not necessary
  • Elastography - to evaluate degree of fibrosis.
  • Lifestyle advice aimed at weight loss with excercise and dieting.
  • Orlistat (enteric lipase inhibitor) is used as adjunct in severely obese to reduce intestinal lipid absorption
  • Can cause vitamin malabsorption.
  • Pioglitazone has been proven to reduce NASH but weight gain CCF, bladder cancer and fracture risk are increased.

Morphology of hepatitis

Acute hepatitis leads to significant destruction with less inflammation.
In Chronic hepatitis, there is more inflammation than destruction.

[!INFO] In acute AND chronic hepatitis, ❗mononulear cells (macrophages) predominate.❗
There is no neutrophil Vs. macrophage predominance in acute Vs. chornic hepatitis like in most orther tissues.

Acute hepatitis

  • Necrotic areas macroscopically have a mushy texture and muddy color.
  • Less inflammation, more hepatocyte death
  • Two forms of cell death are
    • Necrosis - cells undergo ballooning degeneration (cytoplasm looks empty) -> then cytolysis occurs and cells appear to have dropped out, their existence only being marked by the mourning macrophages left behind and the reticulin scaffhold.
    • Apoptosis -
      • Rather than becoming pale and featureless, cells shrink and become intensely eosinophilic.
  • Lobular hepatitis refers to when these cell changes occur in the interior of the lobule, away from the portal tracts.
  • When many cells undergo necrosis (severe necrosi) we get 'confluent' necrosis.
  • When even more cells die, we get central-portal bridging necrosis.
  • Even more necrosis -> parenchymal collapse.
  • In acute hepatitis, portal inflammation is absent.
  • Regeneration depends on whether the scaffhold fibrous tissue is preserved;
    • If it is, regeneration will be orderly.
    • If it is not (i.e in severe acute hepatitis) regeneration is disordered.
    • Aberrant scarring will lead to post hepatitic cirrhosis.

Chronic hepatitis

  • Features nodules and scarring.
  • More inflammation, less death
  • There are dense, mononuclear portal infiltrates. <-❗ defining lesion of chronic hepatitis❗
  • There is interface hepatitis -> (spillover from portal inflammation) unlike lobular hepatitis above, the ?necroris occurs at the parenchyma/ portal stroma interface.
  • Fibrosis occurs: First only within portal tracts but then between portal tracts forming fibrous septa. -> Together with nodule formation, this leads to cirrhosis.
